  "prompt": "What book would be best to start with to learn the mathematics of quantum mechanics?",
  "response": "To begin learning the mathematics of quantum mechanics, a good starting point is \"Quantum Mechanics: Concepts and Applications\" by Nouredine Zettili. This book provides a clear introduction to the fundamental concepts of quantum mechanics while also covering the necessary mathematical tools. \n\nIf you're looking for a more mathematically rigorous approach, \"Quantum Mechanics and Path Integrals\" by Richard P. Feynman and Albert R. Hibbs includes both practical applications and theoretical insights, although it may be a bit advanced for absolute beginners.\n\nFor a more foundational understanding of the required mathematics, consider starting with \"Linear Algebra and its Applications\" by Gilbert Strang, as linear algebra is crucial for understanding quantum mechanics. Additionally, \"Mathematical Methods for Physicists\" by George B. Arfken and Hans J. Weber provides a solid mathematical framework that is often used in physics courses.\n\nUltimately, the best choice depends on your current level of mathematical knowledge and your specific goals.",
